  "kill_strategy": "Use an input where the first 128 elements have margin ≤ 0 (thread_loss = 0) and the next 128 elements have a small positive denormal margin (e.g., 1e-40). This makes the second‑half warps compute a subnormal number, which is significantly slower, increasing the chance that the first‑half warps read before the second‑half writes are visible. If the race manifests, the sum will miss the contributions from the second half, producing a different final loss.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "Asymmetric computation: first half of elements (indices 0-127) produce zero hinge loss, second half produce a tiny denormal loss. This delays the second‑half warps, potentially exposing the missing __syncthreads().",
    "python_code": "def generate_inputs(device):\n    import torch\n    # shape: [128, 1]\n    predictions = torch.zeros(128, 1, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)\n    targets = torch.zeros(128, 1, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)\n    # first half: predictions = 1, targets = 1 -> margin = 0 -> loss = 0\n    predictions[:64] = 1.0\n    targets[:64] = 1.0\n    # second half: predictions = 1, targets = 1 - 1e-40 -> margin = 1e-40 (denormal) -> loss positive\n    predictions[64:] = 1.0\n    targets[64:] = 1.0 - 1e-40\n    return [predictions, targets]"
